\begin{activity} \label{A:1.8.5} Recall from (\ref{eq:circle_arc_length_parameterization}) that an arc length parameterization of a circle in 2-space of radius $a$ centered at the origin is (from (\ref{eq:circle_arc_length_parameterization}))
\[x(s) = a \cos\left(\frac{s}{a}\right)  \ \ \ \ \text{ and } \ \ \ \ y(t) = a \sin\left(\frac{s}{a}\right).\]
Show that the curvature of this circle is the constant $\frac{1}{a}$. Conclude that smaller circles have larger curvature. Does this make sense?



\begin{comment}

We have
\[\vT(s) = \left\langle -\sin\left(\frac{s}{a}\right), \cos\left(\frac{s}{a}\right) \right\rangle.\]
So the curvature of a circle of radius $a$ is
\begin{align*}
\kappa &= \left\lvert \frac{d \vT}{ds} \right\rvert \\
    &= \left\lvert \left\langle -\frac{1}{a}\cos\left(\frac{s}{a}\right), -\frac{1}{a}\sin\left(\frac{s}{a}\right) \right\rangle \right\rvert \\
    &= \frac{1}{a}.
\end{align*}
So, as expected, larger circles have smaller curvature.

\end{comment}


